@{
    ViewBag.Title = "About This Project";
}

<div class="container" style="margin-top:30px;">
    <h1 style="font-weight:700;">About This Yakuza Information System</h1>

    <p style="font-size:17px; margin-top:20px;">
        This web application was created as part of a software development assignment at
        City of Glasgow College. Its purpose is to demonstrate the use of
        <strong>ASP.NET MVC 5</strong>, <strong>Entity Framework</strong>, and
        <strong>Code First</strong> database design while modelling a structured,
        real‑world‑inspired dataset.
    </p>

    <h3 style="margin-top:30px;">Project Overview</h3>
    <p style="font-size:16px;">
        The system represents the organisational structure of traditional Japanese syndicates,
        focusing on their hierarchy, clans, and membership. The aim is not to glamorise or
        promote criminal activity, but to explore how complex organisations can be modelled
        using relational databases and MVC architecture.
    </p>

    <h3 style="margin-top:30px;">Key Features</h3>
    <ul style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.7;">
        <li>Full CRUD functionality for Yakuza organisations, clans, members, and hierarchy levels</li>
        <li>Entity Framework Code First models with relationships and navigation properties</li>
        <li>Database seeding with realistic sample data</li>
        <li>Bootstrap‑styled pages and navigation menu</li>
        <li>Self‑referencing hierarchy model (Parent → Children)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 style="margin-top:30px;">Technical Stack</h3>
    <ul style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.7;">
        <li>ASP.NET MVC 5</li>
        <li>Entity Framework 6 (Code First)</li>
        <li>SQL Server LocalDB</li>
        <li>Razor Views</li>
        <li>Bootstrap for layout and styling</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 style="margin-top:30px;">Educational Purpose</h3>
    <p style="font-size:16px;">
        This project demonstrates practical skills in:
    </p>
    <ul style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.7;">
        <li>Modelling data using C# classes</li>
        <li>Building relationships between entities</li>
        <li>Generating controllers and views using scaffolding</li>
        <li>Seeding and managing a database</li>
        <li>Creating a functional, navigable MVC application</li>
    </ul>

    <p style="margin-top:30px; font-size:16px;">
        This system is intended purely for academic learning and software development practice.
    </p>
</div>
